# DEFINES
PROVIDER Openrouter
API_KEY sk-hypercanvas-ea5ae94a72a89e837e07a226742cfb68cc67d2c327570c24
API_URL https://claude-oauth-api-0xtayzon-production.up.railway.app/api/v1
PROMPT_ENGINEER_MODEL anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5
RUN_BIN claude --dangerously-skip-permissions --effort max --model claude-haiku-4-5
EVAL_BIN claude --dangerously-skip-permissions --effort max --model claude-haiku-4-5
DIR ~/circuitwebsearch
CHECKPOINT on

# Build a web search engine that produces Google-quality results
CIRCUIT Build a search engine that returns results comparable to Google:
  RUN Build a web search engine in Python that crawls, indexes, and ranks web pages with Google-quality results. \
    Requirements: \
    1. Web crawler: fetches pages from seed URLs, follows links, respects robots.txt, handles rate limiting. \
       Crawl at least 500 pages from 3+ seed domains (e.g. Wikipedia, Python docs, HN). Store raw HTML. \
    2. Content extraction: strip HTML to clean text, extract title, headings, meta description, outbound links. \
    3. Inverted index with positional information (for phrase matching and proximity scoring). \
    4. Ranking algorithm combining: \
       - TF-IDF with BM25 scoring \
       - PageRank (compute from the link graph of crawled pages) \
       - Title/heading boost (terms in title/h1 weighted higher) \
       - URL quality signals (shorter paths, known domains score higher) \
       - Phrase proximity bonus (query terms appearing near each other score higher) \
    5. Query engine: supports multi-word queries, quoted phrases, and minus (exclusion) operator. \
    6. Results display: show title, URL, and a relevant snippet with query terms highlighted. \
    7. CLI: `python search.py crawl <seeds_file>`, `python search.py index`, `python search.py query "search terms"` \
    8. Persist everything (crawl store, index, pagerank scores) so each stage can run independently. \
    9. Include a seeds.txt with good starting URLs.
  EVAL Evaluate the search engine quality by comparing against expectations: \
    1. Verify the crawler fetched 200+ pages (check the crawl store). \
    2. Run these queries and check the results make sense: \
       - "python list comprehension" — top results should be Python-related pages \
       - "HTTP status codes" — should return pages about HTTP/web standards \
       - A quoted phrase query like "\"machine learning\"" — results must contain the exact phrase \
       - An exclusion query like "python -snake" — results should be about the programming language, not the animal \
    3. Verify PageRank is computed — hub pages (like index/main pages) should have higher scores than leaf pages. \
    4. Verify ranking quality: for "python tutorial", a page with "Python Tutorial" in its title \
       should rank higher than a page that merely mentions python once in the body. \
    5. Verify snippets contain the query terms. \
    6. Run `python search.py query "test"` and confirm output includes title, URL, snippet, and score.
    RETRY 5
